we've talked, so far, about
going offline, staying offline.

00:38:12.225 --> 00:38:13.600
But actually,
there's another way

00:38:13.600 --> 00:38:15.020
that you can reduce
the switching costs.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:16.020
You really have read the book.

00:38:16.020 --> 00:38:16.330
This is wonderful.

00:38:16.330 --> 00:38:17.730
MATT BRITTIN: I really
have read the book.

00:38:17.730 --> 00:38:19.370
I don't do this when
I don't read the book.

00:38:19.370 --> 00:38:20.040
CAROLINE WEBB: I know,
but it's wonderful.

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:20.940
It feels-- yeah.

00:38:20.940 --> 00:38:23.180
So the other thing
that you can do

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:25.100
to reduce the amount
of time your brain

00:38:25.100 --> 00:38:28.029
is switching from one
thing to the other--

00:38:28.029 --> 00:38:29.320
actually, let me try something.

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:30.720
Can I try something
with the audience?

00:38:30.720 --> 00:38:31.170
MATT BRITTIN: Yes.

00:38:31.170 --> 00:38:31.530
Yes.

00:38:31.530 --> 00:38:32.210
They're not me.

00:38:32.210 --> 00:38:32.660
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah, yeah.

00:38:32.660 --> 00:38:33.584
That's all right.

00:38:33.584 --> 00:38:35.500
MATT BRITTIN: Don't put
me in the threat zone.

00:38:35.500 --> 00:38:36.120
Put them.

00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:37.965
You're in the fear
zone now, audience.

00:38:37.965 --> 00:38:38.840
Get in the fear zone.

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:41.570
CAROLINE WEBB: You don't have
to get up or do anything much,

00:38:41.570 --> 00:38:42.220
I promise.

00:38:42.220 --> 00:38:46.250
So if you say 1-2-3-4-5-6-7
as quickly as you can,

00:38:46.250 --> 00:38:48.771
on my mark-- and
with some energy.

00:38:48.771 --> 00:38:49.270
One--

00:38:49.270 --> 00:38:50.350
AUDIENCE: 1-2-3-4-5-6-7.

00:38:50.350 --> 00:38:51.170
CAROLINE WEBB: OK.

00:38:51.170 --> 00:38:55.760
Then you say A-B-C-D-E-F-G,
similarly energetic.

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:57.632
AUDIENCE: A-B-C-D-E-F-G.

00:38:57.632 --> 00:38:58.810
CAROLINE WEBB: Fantastic.

00:38:58.810 --> 00:38:59.360
So crisp.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:00.900
Like a cult. Wonderful.

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:03.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:03.970
OK.

00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:06.335
Now I'd like you
to mix the two up.

00:39:06.335 --> 00:39:09.710
I'd like you to say
A1, B2, C3, D4-- which

00:39:09.710 --> 00:39:12.680
should take, basically,
the same amount of time.

00:39:12.680 --> 00:39:13.980
OK?

00:39:13.980 --> 00:39:14.920
Go.

00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:17.270
AUDIENCE: A1, B2, C3, D4--

00:39:17.270 --> 00:39:19.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:20.222 --> 00:39:22.222
CAROLINE WEBB: I love the
fact you just gave up.

00:39:22.222 --> 00:39:24.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:25.390 --> 00:39:26.860
MATT BRITTIN: Epic fail.

00:39:26.860 --> 00:39:27.620
Why?

00:39:27.620 --> 00:39:28.411
CAROLINE WEBB: Why?

00:39:28.411 --> 00:39:31.150
Because you're switching
from numbers to letters

00:39:31.150 --> 00:39:32.750
to numbers to letters.

00:39:32.750 --> 00:39:34.850
And so the advice
that comes out of that

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:38.000
is the more you can batch
similar types of tasks

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.482
together, the quicker you
will get through them.

00:39:40.482 --> 00:39:41.190
MATT BRITTIN: Oh.

00:39:41.190 --> 00:39:43.924
CAROLINE WEBB: So
for me, I like to-- I

00:39:43.924 --> 00:39:45.840
like to think about
different zones in my day.

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:47.780
Doesn't always work,
because obviously,

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:48.970
you have unexpected stuff.

00:39:48.970 --> 00:39:51.900
But being a late-night
person, I actually

00:39:51.900 --> 00:39:55.440
find that my peak time for
creative, thoughtful work

00:39:55.440 --> 00:39:56.540
is actually the afternoon.

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:58.456
You will never see that
anywhere written down,

00:39:58.456 --> 00:40:02.840
because all of the advice is
tuned for early-morning people.

00:40:02.840 --> 00:40:05.800
But I know that, and so I
do my meetings and calls

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:07.970
in the morning.

00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:10.540
And it doesn't always
work quite like that,

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:12.420
but that's what I aim for.

00:40:12.420 --> 00:40:14.970
And then I also
have email blitzes

00:40:14.970 --> 00:40:16.345
in the morning
and the afternoon.

00:40:16.345 --> 00:40:18.520
I stay online,
except when I'm going

00:40:18.520 --> 00:40:20.950
offline to do my deep thinking.

00:40:20.950 --> 00:40:23.670
But I really blitz my
email, morning and evening.

00:40:23.670 --> 00:40:26.896
And that just reduces
the time it takes.

00:40:26.896 --> 00:40:27.812
MATT BRITTIN: Top tip.

00:40:30.706 --> 00:40:32.580
AUDIENCE: So much of
what you talked about is

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:34.170
having a good day at work.

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:36.920
Obviously the other part
of having a good life

00:40:36.920 --> 00:40:39.210
is what goes on outside of work.

00:40:39.210 --> 00:40:41.100
What are the key things
you've discovered

00:40:41.100 --> 00:40:45.410
which you think are transferable
to life outside of work

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:47.814
and difficult social situations?

00:40:47.814 --> 00:40:49.480
Personally thinking
of the school gates,

00:40:49.480 --> 00:40:52.216
which seems to be the most
toxic environment I've ever

00:40:52.216 --> 00:40:52.800
encountered.

00:40:52.800 --> 00:40:54.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:55.740
You know, what--

00:40:55.740 --> 00:40:57.989
MATT BRITTIN: You have got
children, just to be clear.

00:40:57.989 --> 00:40:59.546
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:00.528 --> 00:41:02.365
Just to be clear.

00:41:02.365 --> 00:41:02.990
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:06.370
I wasn't browsing, no, man.

00:41:06.370 --> 00:41:09.199
What-- in the terror
zone here, by the way.

00:41:09.199 --> 00:41:10.240
CAROLINE WEBB: Excellent.

00:41:10.240 --> 00:41:11.690
AUDIENCE: What could I
transfer, and particularly

00:41:11.690 --> 00:41:13.890
help my good lady wife with,
who seems to experience

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:15.329
that more than I do?

00:41:15.329 --> 00:41:16.870
CAROLINE WEBB: It's
a great question.

00:41:16.870 --> 00:41:18.470
Actually, you know,
the book at one point

00:41:18.470 --> 00:41:20.303
was called "How to Have
a Good Day at Work."

00:41:20.303 --> 00:41:25.020
But because it became so
obvious that all of this advice

00:41:25.020 --> 00:41:29.460
is just as relevant with your
families and your friends,

00:41:29.460 --> 00:41:32.470
we reframed it, actually.

00:41:32.470 --> 00:41:34.970
The examples in the book are
about professional situations,

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:36.840
but "good person;
bad circumstances,"

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:41.197
incredibly helpful in
family situations, right?

00:41:41.197 --> 00:41:43.780
Someone is behaving in a certain
way, and you think, OK, well,

00:41:43.780 --> 00:41:45.420
what might have
happened with them?

00:41:45.420 --> 00:41:50.350
And actually, I have to
say, lots of my clients

00:41:50.350 --> 00:41:55.540
say that they test things
out on their children

00:41:55.540 --> 00:41:58.660
before they start to use
them with their colleagues.

00:41:58.660 --> 00:42:01.860
So there was a
particular pattern

00:42:01.860 --> 00:42:06.140
I started to see of men talking
about their relationships

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:08.470
with their teenage daughters.

00:42:08.470 --> 00:42:12.030
And specifically, they
often homed in on the advice

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:14.885
about giving them autonomy.

00:42:14.885 --> 00:42:16.885
Which, of course, doesn't
look like just saying,

00:42:16.885 --> 00:42:19.930
you know, just do it
you want, darling.

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:22.590
But asking them
questions, rather

00:42:22.590 --> 00:42:24.910
than telling them what to do.

00:42:24.910 --> 00:42:27.700
Saying, what do you think is
the right way to go about this?

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:29.180
What makes you think that?

00:42:29.180 --> 00:42:31.510
What would be another approach?

00:42:31.510 --> 00:42:34.390
And the fact is that
the things that we've

00:42:34.390 --> 00:42:37.030
been talking about today are
very deep and very universal.

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:39.660
So the power of
autonomy works even

00:42:39.660 --> 00:42:44.042
with a 13-year-old girl,
or a 15-year-old girl.

00:42:44.042 --> 00:42:46.220
Hard to believe, perhaps.

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:49.552
But these things are
very translatable.

00:42:49.552 --> 00:42:50.760
MATT BRITTIN: Recognize that.

00:42:50.760 --> 00:42:53.652
Is that-- any follow-up?

00:42:53.652 --> 00:42:55.110
AUDIENCE: I'm very
happy with that.

00:42:55.110 --> 00:42:57.443
Interestingly, I often try
some of these things at home,

00:42:57.443 --> 00:43:00.680
and my wife's stock response is
now, "Don't try and Google me."

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:03.259
CAROLINE WEBB: Oh my
gosh, that's funny.

00:43:03.259 --> 00:43:04.800
AUDIENCE: But yeah,
I'll keep trying.

00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:05.610
CAROLINE WEBB: You need
to find someone else.

00:43:05.610 --> 00:43:07.073
Try it on your children.

00:43:07.073 --> 00:43:08.444
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:08.444 --> 00:43:10.110
AUDIENCE: She's much
more pliable, yeah.

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:14.275
CAROLINE WEBB: There's a client
of mine who is an Italian guy,

00:43:14.275 --> 00:43:17.880
and he has a small child.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:18.640
Very small.

00:43:18.640 --> 00:43:22.860
And his wife was concerned
that he wasn't speaking

00:43:22.860 --> 00:43:25.320
as early as they were hoping.

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:31.110
And so Francesco
said, I'm going to try

00:43:31.110 --> 00:43:34.280
this approach of really
listening and then playing

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:38.340
back what the child is saying,
and then adding one or two

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:41.610
new words into what I'm saying.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:44.530
So using what they've said,
but then adding a few words.

00:43:44.530 --> 00:43:46.950
So giving this child
a sense of competence

00:43:46.950 --> 00:43:49.590
because you're using the same
words, and then sort of just

00:43:49.590 --> 00:43:52.510
stretching them slightly
by adding in a few more.

00:43:52.510 --> 00:43:57.550
And it did accelerate the little
one's language acquisition

00:43:57.550 --> 00:43:58.800
after that point.

00:43:58.800 --> 00:44:01.220
I think these things are so
fundamental and so basic.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:02.181
So yes, have a go.

00:44:02.181 --> 00:44:03.180
MATT BRITTIN: Thank you.

00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:03.490
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:04.490
MATT BRITTIN: Thank you.

00:44:04.490 --> 00:44:05.760
Any other questions?

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:09.112
I want to talk a little bit
more about the mind-body energy

00:44:09.112 --> 00:44:09.820
thing, if we can.

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:11.864
We talked a bit about
productivity earlier.

00:44:11.864 --> 00:44:14.030
Are there things that we
can notice about ourselves,

00:44:14.030 --> 00:44:15.610
or others, in that respect?

00:44:15.610 --> 00:44:17.010
And how do we keep up?

00:44:17.010 --> 00:44:19.260
You know, the energy that
we need-- particularly here,

00:44:19.260 --> 00:44:20.030
I think-- is quite high.

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:20.360
It's fast-paced.

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:22.120
There's lots of change
all the time, et cetera.

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:23.280
How can we deal with that?

00:44:26.285 --> 00:44:28.660
CAROLINE WEBB: I do think
that-- well, I mentioned breaks

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:30.320
earlier on.

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:32.380
I do think being
smart about planning

00:44:32.380 --> 00:44:36.700
strategic breaks is important
as you look across the day.

00:44:36.700 --> 00:44:39.300
I do think taking every
single opportunity

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:41.300
to do a tiny bit of
physical exercise--

00:44:41.300 --> 00:44:44.300
I mean, for me, honestly,
I'm not a gym type of person.

00:44:44.300 --> 00:44:47.677
So walking, walking
as fast as I can,

00:44:47.677 --> 00:44:50.010
going for a walk around the
block, even going for a walk

00:44:50.010 --> 00:44:51.470
up to a different floor.

00:44:51.470 --> 00:44:52.380
MATT BRITTIN: So can
I check in on this?

00:44:52.380 --> 00:44:54.140
So there's something
about just, like,

00:44:54.140 --> 00:44:56.910
moving which helps you kind
of process things and stuff.

00:44:56.910 --> 00:44:57.240
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah.

00:44:57.240 --> 00:44:57.946
MATT BRITTIN: Then--
but you're also

00:44:57.946 --> 00:44:59.680
sort of saying exercise,
which is a notch up,

00:44:59.680 --> 00:45:00.360
it's not just that.

00:45:00.360 --> 00:45:01.925
There's something about
elevating your heart rate

00:45:01.925 --> 00:45:04.140
and your breathing that's
more than just moving.

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:04.480
CAROLINE WEBB: It can be.

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:07.360
I mean, you know, the evidence
is really encouraging in this.

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:12.660
I read this paper where the
scientists were saying--

00:45:12.660 --> 00:45:15.320
it was actually quite sort
of colloquial language

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:19.740
for a research paper,
saying, more exercise

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:23.030
is better than less, but less
exercise is better than none.

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:26.490
Just this general sense
that any activity is useful

00:45:26.490 --> 00:45:27.340
and stimulating.

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:29.090
So the problem is
often when you kind

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:30.839
of-- especially this
time of year, and you

00:45:30.839 --> 00:45:32.910
have these sort of New
Year's resolutions.

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:34.880
The risk is, you've
set them here.

00:45:34.880 --> 00:45:39.260
And when you fail,
you get this feeling

00:45:39.260 --> 00:45:41.280
of threat and disappointment.

00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:43.320
It's the opposite of reward.

00:45:43.320 --> 00:45:45.590
And then the reason
that that's an issue

00:45:45.590 --> 00:45:47.210
is that reward is motivating.

00:45:47.210 --> 00:45:50.090
That's the way the reward
system works in the brain.

00:45:50.090 --> 00:45:51.802
So you have a small success.

00:45:51.802 --> 00:45:53.010
You feel good about yourself.

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:55.240
You feel motivated to
try the next thing.

00:45:55.240 --> 00:45:57.610
So I would always
encourage people to set

00:45:57.610 --> 00:45:59.430
very small, manageable goals.

00:45:59.430 --> 00:46:02.410
What is it that I actually
think I can really do today?

00:46:02.410 --> 00:46:03.910
And then achieve
that, feel great,

00:46:03.910 --> 00:46:05.743
and then do a tiny bit
more, if you want to.

00:46:05.743 --> 00:46:08.550
But it's always much
better to do that,

00:46:08.550 --> 00:46:10.430
from the perspective
of neuroscience,

00:46:10.430 --> 00:46:12.280
than it is to start
big and work back.

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:14.780
MATT BRITTIN: Now, we're getting
close to being out of time.

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:16.363
There's so much we
haven't touched on.

00:46:16.363 --> 00:46:19.180
But one other area that
we've touched on a bit,

00:46:19.180 --> 00:46:20.930
and we haven't gone
into so much depth on,

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:24.590
is the relationships that
we have around the place,

00:46:24.590 --> 00:46:27.010
and how what you talked
about, in terms of the way

00:46:27.010 --> 00:46:30.090
the brain operates and so
on, affects relationships.

00:46:30.090 --> 00:46:31.800
What are the things
that you've learned

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:35.534
and that you advise
us in that area?

00:46:35.534 --> 00:46:36.950
CAROLINE WEBB:
Well, we've touched

00:46:36.950 --> 00:46:39.160
on a lot of the things
that are relevant.

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:43.570
So your intentions will shape
the way you perceive people.

00:46:43.570 --> 00:46:47.220
The extent to which you
present a threat to them,

00:46:47.220 --> 00:46:50.300
or reward to them, will
make a big difference

00:46:50.300 --> 00:46:51.927
to their behavior.

00:46:51.927 --> 00:46:53.510
But there are other
things in the mix.

00:46:53.510 --> 00:46:56.990
There are very sort of fun
and strange things in the mix.

00:46:56.990 --> 00:47:00.590
I mean, you all know,
if we come on stage

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:05.140
and we had been really
visibly grumpy and stressed,

00:47:05.140 --> 00:47:06.424
what would have happened?

00:47:06.424 --> 00:47:08.090
There would have been
this ripple effect

00:47:08.090 --> 00:47:10.423
where you'd all have been,
like, what-- what's happened?

00:47:10.423 --> 00:47:11.494
What's going on?

00:47:11.494 --> 00:47:13.660
Same thing if you're in a
meeting and someone grumpy

00:47:13.660 --> 00:47:14.160
comes in.

00:47:14.160 --> 00:47:16.450
It just kind of settles
this cloud over the room.

00:47:16.450 --> 00:47:18.800
So research suggests that
you're absolutely right,

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:23.470
that within five minutes,
people's emotions sync up,

00:47:23.470 --> 00:47:25.930
even when you're not
working on the same thing.

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:29.970
And even when you don't
even talk to each other.

00:47:29.970 --> 00:47:32.590
There's lots of disagreement
in the behavioral sciences

00:47:32.590 --> 00:47:33.970
about why this happens.

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:34.680
Because--

00:47:34.680 --> 00:47:35.660
MATT BRITTIN: So it
definitely happens, facts,

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:35.916
but we don't know why.

00:47:35.916 --> 00:47:37.220
CAROLINE WEBB: But it
definitely happens.

00:47:37.220 --> 00:47:39.550
I mean, so there are some who
believe it's mirror neurons.

00:47:39.550 --> 00:47:41.010
Problem is, mirror
neurons haven't

00:47:41.010 --> 00:47:42.680
been found in human beings.

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:44.617
The research has
been done in monkeys.

00:47:44.617 --> 00:47:45.200
There's some--

00:47:45.200 --> 00:47:45.860
MATT BRITTIN: Sorry, hang on.

00:47:45.860 --> 00:47:46.859
That sounds interesting.

00:47:46.859 --> 00:47:48.610
So monkeys have got
something we haven't?

00:47:48.610 --> 00:47:50.651
CAROLINE WEBB: No, we
almost certainly have them,

00:47:50.651 --> 00:47:55.510
but the research involves
invasive explorations which

00:47:55.510 --> 00:47:56.870
have not been done in humans.

00:47:56.870 --> 00:47:57.200
MATT BRITTIN: Right.

00:47:57.200 --> 00:47:58.074
CAROLINE WEBB: Right.

00:47:58.074 --> 00:47:59.180
So--

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:00.700
MATT BRITTIN: Is that something
about telepathy, is it?

00:48:00.700 --> 00:48:01.360
Or--

00:48:01.360 --> 00:48:01.490
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah.

00:48:01.490 --> 00:48:04.390
I mean, you'll read a lot in
the popular press about mirror

00:48:04.390 --> 00:48:06.474
neurons, and the existence
of mirror neurons.

00:48:06.474 --> 00:48:08.140
The truth is that you
can really wind up

00:48:08.140 --> 00:48:10.360
a neuroscientist very quickly
by talking about mirror neurons.

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:10.610
MATT BRITTIN: OK.

00:48:10.610 --> 00:48:11.450
Great.

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:13.275
CAROLINE WEBB: But
even without that--

00:48:13.275 --> 00:48:14.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:14.760
Yes.

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:17.700
Even without that, we know from
psychology, years and years

00:48:17.700 --> 00:48:19.200
of research, that
there is something

00:48:19.200 --> 00:48:20.280
called theory of mind.

00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:22.220
We have this ability
to empathize.

00:48:22.220 --> 00:48:25.110
We have this ability to perceive
the possibility someone else

00:48:25.110 --> 00:48:28.180
has a mind different to ours,
after the age-- well, there's

00:48:28.180 --> 00:48:31.620
a particular age, as a child,
where you start to imagine

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:33.200
someone is different to you.

00:48:33.200 --> 00:48:37.340
Some executives have never
quite got there, but yes.

00:48:37.340 --> 00:48:39.510
There's definitely
this idea that we

00:48:39.510 --> 00:48:42.240
are built social animals,
we are built to sync up

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:43.690
with people around us.

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:46.800
So just knowing that the way
you go in to a conversation

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:51.086
has an enormous effect
on the people around you.

00:48:51.086 --> 00:48:53.449
And there have been
times when I've

00:48:53.449 --> 00:48:54.990
been in a meeting
that's going south.

00:48:54.990 --> 00:48:57.610
And there's a point
where I think, well,

00:48:57.610 --> 00:49:00.280
I can get irritated
or worried about this,

00:49:00.280 --> 00:49:03.390
or I recognize that I can be a
little bit of a force for good

00:49:03.390 --> 00:49:06.590
at this moment, whatever the
science is underneath it,

00:49:06.590 --> 00:49:10.160
and say, OK, what do I want
to radiate into the room?

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:14.010
And just try and bring something
to mind that actually puts you

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:14.640
in that state--

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:16.181
MATT BRITTIN: This
whole thing about,

00:49:16.181 --> 00:49:18.910
you know, if I smile, then I
become happier, that's true,

00:49:18.910 --> 00:49:19.410
isn't it?

00:49:19.410 --> 00:49:20.534
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah, it is.

00:49:20.534 --> 00:49:22.610
I mean, again, there's
this sort of two-way flow

00:49:22.610 --> 00:49:25.030
in the central nervous
system, which is quite weird.

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:28.160
So when we're happy,
we tend to smile.

00:49:28.160 --> 00:49:30.590
When we relax, we tend
to breathe deeply.

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:33.470
When we're confident,
we tend to stand tall.

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:35.970
And it seems that the
relationship goes the other way

00:49:35.970 --> 00:49:36.660
around, as well.

00:49:36.660 --> 00:49:38.780
So when we mimic the
activities associated

00:49:38.780 --> 00:49:41.990
with being happy,
relaxed, and confident,

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:44.360
we-- again, debate
on exactly how

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:47.140
this works-- our brain
interprets that as a signal

00:49:47.140 --> 00:49:49.550
we can be happy,
confident, and relaxed.

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:51.090
And so smiling, yes.

00:49:51.090 --> 00:49:53.730
A little bit of-- you know,
finding a reason to smile,

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:56.244
even if it's a bit lame,
can quickly end up--

00:49:56.244 --> 00:49:58.160
MATT BRITTIN: Now I'm
very self-conscious now.

00:49:58.160 --> 00:49:59.160
CAROLINE WEBB: No, yeah.

00:49:59.160 --> 00:49:59.674
I know.

00:49:59.674 --> 00:50:00.880
Hey.

